          <lastSummaryUpdateDate>2020-12-09T20:50:41Z</lastSummaryUpdateDate>
          <text><![CDATA[<p><b>Consumer Relief during COVID-19 Act </b></p> <p>This bill places restrictions on the collection of consumer debts during the COVID-19 (i.e., coronavirus disease 2019) emergency period and for 120 days after this period. Among other things, debt collectors may not during this period </p> <ul> <li>enforce a security interest through a repossession, </li> <li>seize assets, </li> <li>commence or continue an eviction, </li> <li>terminate utility service, or </li> <li>charge fees or apply a higher interest rate as a result of nonpayment. </li> </ul> <p>After this period, debt collectors must provide certain repayment options including extending the repayment period for debts. </p> <p>The bill also provides for forbearance programs established by creditors for consumers experiencing a financial hardship due to COVID-19. The Federal Reserve Board must establish a credit facility to make long-term, low-cost loans to these creditors for losses caused by any forbearance of payments. </p>]]></text>
          <updateDate>2020-07-27T04:00:00Z</updateDate>
          <name>Introduced in House</name>
        </item>
      </billSummaries>
